  "signature": "ed25519:b4e2d1f3a6c8e0b2d4f6a8c0e2b4d6f8a0c2e4b6d8f0a2c4e6b8d0f2a4c6e8b0",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 is a commercially validated FEA solver with ISO 9001-certified QMS documentation. The FDA-internal solver (Abaqus 2021) was verified against NAFEMS benchmark suite LE1–LE10 with all results within 0.5% of analytical solutions. DePuy Synthes Ansys installation is covered by a site-specific software validation plan (SVP-2021-0047) that includes regression testing for contact mechanics and large-deformation plasticity. Version control records, build logs, and test reports are archived in the project document management system. Required Gradation 2 (documented commercial solver with basic QMS); achieved Gradation 3 (multi-solver cross-verification plus regression suite).",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/nagaraja-sqa",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "All FEA solvers must be covered by a documented QMS and must pass NAFEMS benchmark tests LE1–LE10 within 1% of analytical reference values. Software version must be recorded and frozen at the time of simulation runs.",
        "threshold": "NAFEMS benchmark error < 1%; QMS documentation present for all three solver installations"
      }
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Numerical code verification was performed via the Method of Manufactured Solutions (MMS) for the elastoplastic constitutive model and via comparison to closed-form Euler-Bernoulli beam solutions for the bending-dominated load case. Observed convergence rates matched theoretical second-order rates (p=2.01 ± 0.04) across three mesh refinement levels. Cross-solver agreement between Ansys and Abaqus on an identical mesh was within 0.3% for all QoIs. Required Gradation 2 (benchmark comparison); achieved Gradation 3 (MMS plus multi-solver cross-verification with convergence rate confirmation).",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/nagaraja-ncv",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Observed convergence rate must be within 10% of the theoretical rate for the discretisation scheme employed. Cross-solver QoI agreement must be within 1% on a common mesh.",
        "threshold": "Convergence rate p within [1.8, 2.2]; cross-solver difference < 1%"
      }
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "A systematic mesh convergence study was conducted using four mesh densities (global element edge lengths 0.8, 0.5, 0.35, and 0.25 mm). Richardson extrapolation was applied to estimate the discretisation error for each QoI. The Grid Convergence Index (GCI) for the production mesh (0.35 mm) was 0.8% for stiffness, 1.1% for yield force, and 0.9% for force at 40 mm displacement — all well below the 3% acceptance threshold. The production mesh contains 284,000 second-order tetrahedral elements with local refinement at the screw-rod interface and thread roots. Required Gradation 2 (mesh convergence study); achieved Gradation 3 (Richardson extrapolation with GCI quantification on multiple QoIs).",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/nagaraja-disc",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "GCI for the production mesh must be less than 3% for all primary QoIs. Mesh convergence study must include at least three systematically refined meshes.",
        "threshold": "GCI < 3% for stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement"
      }
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "Iterative solver convergence was monitored for all simulation runs. Newton-Raphson residual norms were required to drop below 1e-6 (force) and 1e-8 (displacement) within each load increment. All 33 ensemble runs (11 geometric replicates × 3 solver configurations) converged without divergence or cutback beyond the first load increment. Automatic time-stepping was used with a minimum step size of 0.01 mm crosshead displacement; no step-size sensitivity was detected above this floor. Required Gradation 1 (convergence monitoring); achieved Gradation 2 (documented residual criteria plus step-size sensitivity check).",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/nagaraja-nse",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Newton-Raphson force residual norm must be below 1e-6 at convergence for every load increment. No divergence or unconverged increments permitted in production runs.",
        "threshold": "Force residual norm < 1e-6; zero unconverged increments across all 33 runs"
      }
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "A documented simulation plan (SP-2023-NC-001) specifying all model setup steps — geometry import, material assignment, boundary condition application, contact pair definition, and post-processing — was prepared prior to simulation execution and reviewed by an independent analyst. Two analysts independently set up the model from the same CAD and material data; QoI agreement between independent setups was within 0.4%. A pre-simulation checklist was completed and archived for each of the 33 runs. Required Gradation 2 (documented simulation plan with independent review); achieved Gradation 2.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/nagaraja-use-error",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "A documented simulation plan must be prepared and independently reviewed before execution. Independent analyst replication must agree within 1% on all primary QoIs.",
        "threshold": "Independent replication QoI difference < 1%; simulation plan review sign-off documented"
      }
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "The model form — quasi-static implicit FEA with isotropic bilinear elastoplastic constitutive law for Ti-6Al-4V, frictional Coulomb contact at screw-rod and screw-block interfaces, and geometric nonlinearity (large deformation) — was selected based on prior published validation studies of pedicle screw constructs (Goel 1995, Rohlmann 2001, Nagaraja 2019). The appropriateness of the quasi-static assumption was verified by comparing kinetic energy to internal energy throughout the simulated displacement ramp; KE/IE remained below 0.5% confirming inertial effects are negligible. Plasticity model parameters were identified from tensile coupon data (N=5 Ti-6Al-4V dog-bone specimens). Required Gradation 2 (model form justified by literature); achieved Gradation 3 (model form justified plus independent experimental verification of constitutive parameters).",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/nagaraja-model-form",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Model form selection must be justified by peer-reviewed literature or prior validation studies. Quasi-static assumption must be verified by KE/IE ratio check. Constitutive parameters must be sourced from independent material testing.",
        "threshold": "KE/IE < 1% throughout simulation; constitutive parameter source documented with traceability to coupon test data"
      }
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "All model inputs are traceable to primary sources. Ti-6Al-4V elastic modulus (114 GPa) and yield stress (880 MPa) sourced from ASTM B265 material certificate lot-specific testing (N=5 coupons, CV < 2%). UHMWPE block modulus (0.93 GPa) measured by compression testing per ASTM D695 (N=5 specimens). Screw geometry digitised from manufacturer-supplied CMM report (tolerance ±0.02 mm). Friction coefficient (0.18) taken from tribological literature (Bhushan 2013) with ±0.06 uncertainty bound propagated through Monte Carlo UQ. Rod modulus (210 GPa CoCr) from manufacturer certificate. Required Gradation 2 (inputs documented with sources); achieved Gradation 3 (lot-specific material testing plus full uncertainty characterisation for all inputs).",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/nagaraja-model-inputs",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "All model inputs must be traceable to a primary source (material certificate, published standard, or direct measurement). Uncertainty bounds must be documented for each input and propagated through the UQ analysis.",
        "threshold": "100% of inputs have documented source; uncertainty bounds defined for all inputs with CV > 1%"
      }
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were tested across two independent laboratories (Lab 1: N=6, FDA CDRH; Lab 2: N=5, DePuy Synthes). All constructs were assembled from the same production lot (lot 2022-NC-07) and inspected by CMM prior to testing; dimensional conformance to nominal within ±0.03 mm confirmed for all 11 specimens. Inter-laboratory CV for stiffness was 3.1%, yield force 2.8%, and force at 40 mm 3.4% — consistent with typical ASTM F1717 inter-laboratory precision. Sample size justification: power analysis (alpha=0.05, beta=0.20, effect size 10%) requires N=9; N=11 exceeds this. Required Gradation 2 (multiple specimens, documented lot); achieved Gradation 3 (multi-laboratory, CMM-inspected, power-justified sample size).",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/nagaraja-test-samples",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Minimum N=9 specimens (power-justified) from a single documented lot, CMM-inspected for dimensional conformance. Inter-laboratory CV must be below 5% for all primary QoIs.",
        "threshold": "N >= 9; inter-laboratory CV < 5%; CMM conformance within ±0.05 mm of nominal"
      }
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single set of ASTM F1717 conditions (10 mm/min, ambient, 60 mm moment arm). While the protocol was fully documented and controlled, only one loading rate and one environmental condition were explored. A required Gradation 3 would demand at least two independent test conditions (e.g., varied loading rate or temperature) to assess condition sensitivity. The achieved Gradation 2 reflects complete documentation and controlled execution of a single condition. This shortfall is addressed in the offset rationale in the decision record, where the low sensitivity of QoIs to loading rate (confirmed by the sensitivity analysis) and the ASTM-standardised nature of the test condition justify acceptance despite the gap.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/nagaraja-test-conditions",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Test conditions must be fully documented per ASTM F1717. Ideally, at least two independent condition sets (loading rate or temperature variation) should be explored to assess sensitivity. A single condition is acceptable only if sensitivity analysis confirms low QoI dependence on the varied parameter.",
        "threshold": "Full ASTM F1717 protocol documentation; sensitivity analysis confirms QoI change < 5% across plausible condition range"
      },
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-noncannulated-accepted/factor/test-conditions"
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Equivalency between model inputs and experimental parameters was established through a systematic parameter mapping table. Screw geometry in the FEA was derived directly from the CMM report of the tested specimens (not nominal CAD), ensuring geometric fidelity. UHMWPE block modulus in the FEA was set to the value measured from the same material batch used in testing. Insertion torque (8 N·m) was replicated in the FEA via a pre-stress step that imposed equivalent thread preload. Crosshead displacement rate was matched exactly (10 mm/min). All mapping decisions are documented in the simulation plan (SP-2023-NC-001, Section 4.2). Required Gradation 2 (input mapping documented); achieved Gradation 3 (specimen-specific geometry and batch-specific material properties used in FEA).",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/nagaraja-equiv-inputs",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "A parameter mapping table must document the correspondence between every experimental condition and its FEA counterpart. Specimen-specific geometry and batch-specific material data must be used where available.",
        "threshold": "100% of experimental parameters mapped to FEA inputs; specimen-specific CMM data used for geometry; batch-specific material data used for UHMWPE modulus"
      }
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Quantitative output comparison was performed using two metrics: (1) relative error between FEA ensemble mean and experimental mean, required < 10%; and (2) validation metric E/uval (ASME V&V 10.1 approach), required < 1.96. For stiffness: error 2.0%, E/uval 0.74. For yield force: error 1.9%, E/uval 0.88. For force at 40 mm: error 1.3%, E/uval 0.61. All three QoIs pass both acceptance criteria. Graphical comparison of full load-displacement curves was also performed; FEA prediction band encloses all 11 experimental curves from 0 to 40 mm displacement. Required Gradation 2 (quantitative comparison with documented metric); achieved Gradation 3 (multiple metrics including uncertainty-normalised validation metric, full curve comparison, and multi-laboratory pooled analysis).",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/nagaraja-output-comparison",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Relative error between FEA ensemble mean and experimental mean must be < 10% for all primary QoIs. Uncertainty-normalised validation metric E/uval must be < 1.96 for all QoIs.",
        "threshold": "Relative error < 10%; E/uval < 1.96 for stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement"
      }
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "The three QoIs — construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement — are directly specified in ASTM F1717 as the required outputs for compression-bending characterisation of spinal implant constructs. Clinical relevance is established: construct stiffness correlates with load sharing and fusion environment; yield force defines the structural safety margin against permanent deformation; force at 40 mm is the regulatory benchmark for gross failure. All three QoIs are directly measurable in the bench test and directly computable from the FEA. The mapping between QoI and clinical risk is documented in the risk analysis (RA-2023-NC-001). Required Gradation 2 (QoIs documented and linked to test standard); achieved Gradation 3 (QoIs linked to clinical risk analysis and regulatory benchmark).",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/nagaraja-qoi-relevance",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "QoIs must be directly specified in or derivable from ASTM F1717 and must be linked to documented clinical risk. QoIs must be directly measurable in the experimental setup and directly computable from the FEA without post-processing assumptions.",
        "threshold": "All three QoIs present in ASTM F1717; clinical risk linkage documented in risk analysis"
      }
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "The validation activity is a direct validation: the FEA model predicts the same physical scenario (ASTM F1717 compression-bending of the exact non-cannulated 7.5 mm construct) as the COU. The experimental specimens are from the same production lot as the device under regulatory review. The loading conditions, fixture geometry, and boundary conditions in the FEA replicate the bench test without extrapolation. No analogy or surrogate validation is required. The validation evidence directly supports the COU claim without gap analysis. Required Gradation 2 (validation directly relevant to COU); achieved Gradation 3 (direct validation with same-lot specimens and exact COU loading conditions, no extrapolation required).",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
